{{Infobox NRHP | name =MacDowell Colony | nrhp_type = nhld | nocat = yes | image = MacDowell Colony.jpg | caption = Colony Hall and Sigma Alpha Iota Cottage | location= 100 High Street, [[Peterborough, New Hampshire]] | locmapin = New Hampshire#USA | area = | built =1907 | designated_nrhp_type= December 29, 1962<ref name="nhlsum">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=28&ResourceType=District|title=MacDowell Colony|accessdate=2007-10-22|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606064136/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=28&ResourceType=District|archivedate=2011-06-06|df=}}</ref> | added = October 15, 1966<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2007a}}</ref> | governing_body = Private | refnum=66000026 }} {{coord|42|53|24|N|71|57|18|W|type:landmark|display=title}} The '''MacDowell Colony''' is an [[artists' colony]] in [[Peterborough, New Hampshire]], United States, founded in 1907 by [[Marian MacDowell]], pianist and wife of composer [[Edward MacDowell]]. She established the institution and its endowment chiefly with donated funds. She led the colony for almost 25 years, against a background of two world wars, the [[Great Depression]], and other challenges.
The mission of The MacDowell Colony is to nurture the arts by offering creative individuals of the highest talent an inspiring environment in which they can produce enduring works of the imagination.
Over the years, an estimated 7,700 artists have been supported in residence, including the winners of at least 79 [[Pulitzer Prize]]s, 781 Guggenheim Fellowships, 100 Rome Prizes, 30 National Book Awards, 26 Tony Awards, 24 MacArthur Fellowships, 9 Grammys, 8 Oscars, and 8 National Medals for the Arts.<ref>[http://www.macdowellcolony.org/about/faqs MacDowell Colony FAQ]</ref> The colony has accepted visual and interdisciplinary artists, architects, filmmakers, composers, playwrights, poets, and writers, both well-known and unknown.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7686354|title= Artists Retreat into Solitude at MacDowell Colony|author=Silverman, Art |work=All Things Considered|date= March 6, 2007}}</ref>
==Awards== In 1962, the colony was designated a [[National Historic Landmark]].<ref name="nhlsum"/><ref name="nrhpinv2">{{cite book| authors=Bradford, S. Sydney & Rettig, Polly M.| date=January 6, 1976| url={{NHLS url|id=66000026}}| title= National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: MacDowell Colony| publisher= National Park Service}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url={{NHLS url|id=66000026|photos=y}}| title=Accompanying 5 photos, from 1907 and 1975| work=National Register of Historical Places Inventory-Nomination: MacDowell Colony |publisher=National Park Service| date=January 6, 1976| authors=Bradford, S. Sydney & Rettig, Polly}}</ref>
In 1997, the colony was awarded the [[National Medal of Arts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nea.gov/honors/medals/medalists_year.html#97 |website=NEA.gov |title=Lifetime Honors |author=National Medal of Arts |date=1997 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130826194408/http://www.nea.gov/honors/medals/medalists_year.html |archivedate=2013-08-26 |df= }}</ref>
== Notable works == [[Image:PeterboroughNH MacdowellColony MainHouse.jpg|thumb|right|Bond Hall in 2012]]
* [[Aaron Copland]] worked there on composing the orchestral suite ''[[Appalachian Spring]]'' (1944), a [[1945 Pulitzer Prize|1945]] Pulitzer winner.<ref>http://www.pulitzer.org/bycat/Music</ref> * [[Spalding Gray]] worked on his novel ''The Impossible Vacation'' and later chronicled his experiences at MacDowell Colony in his extended monologue ''[[Monster in a Box]]''.<ref>http://www.macdowellcolony.org/about-ArtistsWorks.html</ref> * [[Leonard Bernstein]] completed his Mass. * [[Thornton Wilder]] wrote ''Our Town'' and ''The Bridge of San Luis Rey.'' * [[James Baldwin]] wrote ''Giovanni’s Room.'' * [[Willa Cather]] wrote ''Death Comes for the Archbishop.'' * Dubose and Dorothy Heyward wrote ''Porgy and Bess.'' * [[Virgil Thomson]] worked on ''Mother of Us All'' * [[Alice Walker]] worked on her first novel and ''Meridian'' at MacDowell * [[Michael Chabon]] wrote ''The Amazing Adventures of Kavalier & Clay, a 2001 Pulitzer winner.'' Chabon became Chairman of the Colony in 2010.<ref>Carolyn Kellog (December 7, 2010), [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/jacketcopy/2010/12/michael-chabon-is-the-new-chair-of-the-macdowell-colony-board.html Michael Chabon named chairman of MacDowell Colony board], ''Los Angeles Times''.</ref> * Alice Sebold wrote ''The Lovely Bones.'' * Jonathan Franzen completed ''The Corrections''.
== History == The composer Edward MacDowell was one of the first seven members of the [[American Academy of Arts and Letters]]. He believed that interdisciplinary associations among artists were valuable.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}
In 1896, Marian MacDowell bought Hillcrest Farm in Peterborough, New Hampshire, as a summer residence for herself and her husband. She had always been careful to give him a quiet room for his work. Edward MacDowell found that the New Hampshire landscape enhanced his work of composing music.
The couple formulated a plan to provide an interdisciplinary experience in a nurturing landscape, by creating an institutionalized residential [[art colony]] in the area. In 1904, Edward MacDowell began to show signs of an illness that ended his composing and teaching career. He would die in 1908.<ref>{{cite web|title=Library Of Congress|url=http://memory.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.natlib.ihas.200035715/default.html|website=Library Of Congress}}</ref>
In 1907, Marian MacDowell deeded their farm to the Edward MacDowell Association and founded the MacDowell Colony. The first guests arrived that year: sisters [[Helen Farnsworth Mears]], a sculptor, and Mary Mears, a writer. MacDowell began by inviting applicants personally, but by the 1920s had consigned the admission process to a committee.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}
Marian and friends raised funds among a wide variety of people for the colony, which was supported by industrialist and philanthropist [[Andrew Carnegie]], former [[U.S. President]] [[Grover Cleveland]], financier [[J. P. Morgan]], other prominent people, as well as many others across the country. MacDowell said the most consistent support came from women's clubs and professional music sororities (see, for example, the [[MacDowell Club]] of New York). At the age of 50, MacDowell began lecturing to women's groups to raise funds, resumed her performing career, and became a noted interpreter of her husband's work.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}
By 1918, 31 of [[Isabelle Sprague Smith]]'s students funded the creation of the Isabelle D. Sprague Smith studio.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Musical Monitor|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DnpFAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA357|year=1918|publisher=Mrs. David Allen Campbell, Publisher|page=357|chapter=Studios}}</ref> Through the years more separate studios were built. The program continues in 32 studios scattered over {{convert|450|acre|sqkm}} of land.{{citation needed|date=April 2015}}
== Medal Day == {{main article |Edward MacDowell Medal}} Every year, the colony presents the [[Edward MacDowell Medal]] to an artist who has made a significant cultural contribution. Residency at the colony is not a requirement. Medal Day is one of the rare occasions when the colony is open to the public. The ceremony includes a keynote speech, after which the artists open their studios to visitors.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.macdowellcolony.org/md.html| title=Medal Day| publisher=The MacDowell Colony| accessdate=2008-03-17| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080407060154/http://www.macdowellcolony.org/md.html| archivedate=2008-04-07| df=}}</ref>
==Property-tax exemption dispute== The colony, a [[non-profit organization]], enjoys the status of a [[charitable organization|charity]], entitling it to exemption from local [[property tax]]es, among other things. However, in 2005, the town of Peterborough's [[board of selectmen|selectmen]] (local-government executives) decided to challenge MacDowell's charitable status and billed the colony for a "payment in lieu of taxes". A lawyer for the town argued that "the colony certainly benefits its artists-in-residence, but that doesn't strike us as being the general public."<ref>{{cite web| author=Winkleman, E. |date=November 1, 2005|url=http://www.edwardwinkleman.com/2005_11_01_archive.html| title= Local Government: McDowell Not Advancing Spiritual or Intellectual Well-Being of General Public| website=EdwardWinkleman.com}}</ref>
The colony's board of directors paid the bill, then successfully challenged the charge.<ref>{{cite news| title=Town Demands Taxes from Long-Exempt Artists' Colony| date=October 13, 2005| author=Brooks, Anthony (Author) & Inskeep, Steve (Host)| work=All Things Considered| publisher=NPR| url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=4956854}}</ref> A 2007 [[New Hampshire Superior Court|Superior Court]] opinion found that the MacDowell Colony, by promoting the arts, was a charitable institution, a ruling that was upheld by the [[New Hampshire Supreme Court]] in a subsequent appeal.<ref name=supcourt>{{cite web| url=http://www.courts.state.nh.us/supreme/opinions/2008/macdo024.pdf| title=Town of Peterborough v. The MacDowell Colony, Inc.| date=2008-03-14|format=PDF| publisher=The Supreme Court of New Hampshire| accessdate=2008-03-17}}</ref>{{rp|p13}} The appeal court found that "Contrary to the Town's assertions, MacDowell's articles of incorporation oblige it to use its property for its stated charitable purpose."<ref name=supcourt/>{{rp|p11}}
